<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1898-02-04T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1898-02-04T00:00:00-05:00" n="999" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d999">
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Day</persName> to General
                                    <persName type="to">Lee</persName>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1898-02-04"><hi rend="italic">February 4,
                                1898</hi></date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <p>Secretary of the Navy thinks not prudent for a vessel to remain long in
                            Havana; sanitary reasons. Should some vessel be kept there all the time?
                            If another sent, what have you to suggest as to kind of ship? Telegraph
                            your views.</p>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>